We&#x27;re talking <i>languages</i> here; the way a grammar construct helps the programmer.<p>The C# async language effectively writes a whole batch of code that you&#x27;d need to write yourself in other languages; try/catch blocks, callback functions, thread synchronization code, code to wait for results, etc. In effect, it makes into a language feature something that has previously been considered a design pattern.<p>So something like this in C# 5;<p><pre><code>    01 var foo = await LongProcess1();
    02 var bar = await LongProcess2(foo);
    03 var baz = await LongProcess(bar);
</code></pre>
does a significant amount of work. If I were to code it without the language support, I&#x27;d be writing a great deal of crufty code to handle errors, to make sure one thread completes before using the result in another thread (see foo set on line 01 and used on line 02 for an example) and it avoids the callback hell problem of languages like JavaScript, which become apparent in Node.js programming, for instance.<p>I&#x27;d be interested to know what other mainstream languages have as complete a solution for asynchronous programming -- afaik, JS, Python, Ruby, Java, and C++ don&#x27;t have this. I&#x27;m guessing erlang probably has it built right in, but I&#x27;m not sure. Anyone care to share?
